{
  "text": "PKC\u03b4 is ubiquitously expressed and activated in response to a broad variety of stimuli. In response to specific stimuli, several tyrosine residues in PKC\u03b4 can be phosphorylated by different tyrosine kinases ( Fig. 1 ), leading to individual phosphorylation patterns and possibly differential activation of downstream targets. Among its main roles, PKC\u03b4 is responsible for the regulation of survival, proliferation, and apoptosis in a variety of cells including lymphocytes (reviewed in [CITATION_1] ) (Fig. 2) .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "38335370"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "38335370": {
      "title": "PKC-delta and PKC-epsilon: foes of the same family or strangers?",
      "abstract": "Protein kinase C (PKC) is a family of 10 serine/threonine kinases divided into 3 subfamilies, classical, novel and atypical classes. Two PKC isozymes of the novel group, PKCe and PKC\u03b4, have different and sometimes opposite effects. PKCe stimulates cell growth and differentiation while PKC\u03b4 is apoptotic. In the heart, they are among the most expressed PKC isozymes and they are opposed in the preconditioning process with a positive role of PKCe and an inhibiting role of PKC\u03b4. The goal of this review is to analyze the structural differences of these 2 enzymes that may explain their different behaviors and properties."
    }
  }
}